Title: How do I implement yield-like behavior in Java?
Body: <p>What is the Java way to produce values lazily like Python generators? For example, I'm trying to understand this Java code:</p>
<pre><code>Iterable&lt;Node&gt; getChildCandidates(double distance, double minDist, double maxDist) {
    List&lt;Node&gt; children = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    if (leftChild != null &amp;&amp; distance - maxDist &lt; median) {
        children.add(leftChild);
    }
    if (rightChild != null &amp;&amp; distance + maxDist &gt;= median) {
        children.add(rightChild);
    }
    return children;
}
</code></pre>
<p>And this is the caller:</p>
<pre><code>List&lt;Value&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
Deque&lt;Node&gt; candidates = new ArrayDeque&lt;&gt;();
candidates.push(this);

while (!candidates.isEmpty()) {
    Node node = candidates.pop();
    double distance = node.getDist(obj);
    if (distance &lt;= maxDist &amp;&amp; distance &gt;= minDist) {
        result.addAll(node.values);
    }
    for (Node child : node.getChildCandidates(distance, minDist, maxDist)) {
        candidates.push(child);
    }
}
return result;
</code></pre>
<p>What happens when <code>getChildCandidates</code> is called?
Is a list returned, a single element, or something lazy?
When does iteration stop, and how would you implement true lazy iteration in Java?</p>

