Title: Separation of business logic and data access in Spring / JPA  
Body: <p>I am writing a project in Java using Spring and JPA, and I see that 80% of the code ends up inside my entity classes. This code is confusing and, after a certain time, I cease to understand what is really happening.</p>
<p>Here is what bothers me:</p>
<ol>
<li>I find it ugly that my persistence level (which was supposed to be responsible only for working with database data) is also sending email, calling external APIs, etc.</li>
<li>Also, I find it unacceptable to place business logic in the controller, because this way it becomes difficult to control. For example, in my application there are at least three ways to create new instances of <code>User</code>, but technically it should create them uniformly.</li>
<li>I do not always notice when the methods and properties of my entities become non-deterministic and when they develop side effects.</li>
</ol>
<p>Here is a simple example. At first, the <code>User</code> entity was like this:</p>
<pre><code>public class User {

    public String getPresentName() {
        return name != null ? name : "Anonymous";
    }

    public void activate() {
        status = "activated";
        // persisted by repository
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Over time, it turned into this:</p>
<pre><code>public class User {

    public String getPresentName() {
        // property became non-deterministic in terms of database
        // data is taken from another service by API
        return remoteApi.requestUserName(uid) != null ? remoteApi.requestUserName(uid) : "Anonymous";
    }

    public void activate() {
        // method now has a side effect (send message to user)
        status = "activated";
        // persisted by repository
        mailSender.send("Your account is activated!", "...", email);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>What I want is to separate entities in my code:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Database level entities, i.e. persistence level logic: What kind of data does my application store?</strong></li>
<li><strong>Application level entities, i.e. business level logic: What does my application do?</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>What are the good practices to implement such an approach that can be applied in Spring / JPA?</p>

Title: How to deal with warnings when modifying a Tablesaw column after subsetting
